We first comparatively studied the pristine SCO and the Si-incorporated SCO with an intentional doping amount of 5% at the B-site (i.e., y = 0.05 in SrCo1–ySiyO3–δ, denoted as Si–SCO). Both samples were synthesised by a ball-milling-assisted solid-state reaction method (Methods section). X-ray diffraction (XRD) pattern as shown in Fig. 1a and the corresponding Rietveld refinement analysis (Supplementary Fig. 1a and Table 1) suggest that the parent SCO perovskite consists of a major Sr6Co5O15 phase and a small quantity of Co3O4 impurity, in line with previously reported results36. Incorporating Si into the B-site gave rise to the formation of a tetragonal phase, which has a space group of P4/mmm and lattice parameters of a = ap ≈ 3.85917(4) Å and c ≈ 2ap = 7.7270(1) Å (ap being the lattice parameter of an ideal cubic-phase single perovskite with space group of Pm3¯\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
